{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01B8CxLcVQAUibv7teFeYPPU","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see the problem! At line 681, it applies `stripParentheticalGloss` to the text before adding it as a candidate:\n\n```typescript\nconst singleText = repairOcrText(stripParentheticalGloss(stripTrailingPageRef(stripPageNumber(line.text))));\n```\n\nThe text `\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\"` becomes standalone. But the merged form `\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\"` doesn't have a parenthetical gloss, so it stays as is.\n\n\nBoth candidates get added with \"single\" origin, so my filter should catch this. But there's also the 2-line join logic at lines 725-736 that could be generating additional candidates when consecutive lines are combined, which might be why the filter isn't working as expected.\n\nLooking at the specific case with the two egg dishes, the 2-line join would create an extremely long concatenated string that would fail the hard filters. So I'd end up with two candidates in the selected array: the standalone shorter version and the merged longer version. My filter at lines 1501-1529 should identify the standalone as the survivor since the merged one starts with it plus additional text beginning with \"&\".\n\nChecking the survivingMergedSingles logic...\n\nFiltering for singles where another single candidate extends it by starting with the original text plus a space, followed by a continuation character like \"/\" or \"&\". So for the \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\" candidate, I'd check if any other single starts with that exact text plus a space and then has a continuation character. Check `other = \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\"`\n  - `o = \"baked eggs with feta, harissa tomato sauce & coriander\"`\n  - `o.startsWith(t + \" \")` — `t + \" \" = \"baked eggs with feta, harissa tomato sauce \"`\n  - `o` = `\"baked eggs with feta, harissa tomato sauce & coriander\"`\n  - Does `o` start with `\"baked eggs with feta, harissa tomato sauce \"`? YES!\n  - `remainder = \"& coriander\"`\n  - `/^[/&+:(]/.test(\"& coriander\")` → YES (`&` matches)\n  - Returns true → the standalone is added to `survivingMergedSingles`\n\nSo `survivingMergedSingles` holds the standalones that have a continuation form. Now in the filter at line 1519, I'm checking each selected item — if it's a single, I need to remove it if there's a matching merged item in `survivingMergedSingles` that starts with the single's text followed by a separator character.\n\nWait, I see the issue now. `survivingMergedSingles` contains the standalones, not the merged extensions, so when I check if `m` (a standalone) starts with `s` (another standalone), they're the same thing and the startsWith check fails because there's no space after the text.\n\nI need to flip the logic: find which standalones have extensions that exist, then filter those standalones out of the selected list since they're prefixes of longer merged forms.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1494,"cache_read_input_tokens":43191,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1494},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"04298fa1-86d9-4110-91db-17d42e86a59f","uuid":"8f0a7792-4d7e-453b-8da4-42937684aab0"}
